INSERT INTO akkadian_lexicon.web_content (content,title) VALUES ('<p>The aim of this project - the Akkadian lexicon - is to create a web application based on a database that allows users to search two of the main sources of ancient Mesopotamian history and culture: Assyrian royal inscriptions and Babylonian literary texts. These two vast corpora, along with many others, were written in the Akkadian language, which was the most important language throughout three and a half thousand years of Mesopotamian and Ancient Near Eastern history and culture. It is important to note that the application mainly caters to the needs of the small scientific circle (assyriologists, historians). However, it is also available to anyone interested in the topic. Regarding the project''s background, I began laying the foundation for the database in the summer of 2000 after completing my first year as a student of the Department of Assyriology and Hebrew Studies at Eötvös Lóránd University. I continued this work over the next twenty or so years, with occasional interruptions while working in the electronic game development and digital VFX industries as a 3D graphic artist. Users may search for a word in two ways using the database materials: through simple or composite searches. The simple search works essentially like a traditional vocabulary; after the user types in the singular nominative form of a noun or adjective, or the nominative form of its infinitive in the case of verbs, the application will provide the proper English translation of the Akkadian word using a virtual keyboard. This will be done in the traditional form required by paper-based vocabularies. The composite search, on the other hand, is a real step forward. It allows users to search for specified word forms in the database and provides options for filtering, such as by epoch or genre.</p>','home_text'), ('<p>Our team, Shaolin Masters, which created this web application, consists of six members who met at the the Progmatic Academy’s Java Junior Back-end developer’s course. This application – the Akkadian Lexicon – is the team’s exam work. The members of Shaolin Masters are as follows:</p><p>- <strong>Tamás Marincsák</strong>: former student of Information Technology and Pharmacy who was a true engine of the project. His knowledge on the field of IT was quintessential for the success of the project.</p><p>- <strong>Gergely Müller</strong>: who recently spent five years as a CNC programmer in Austria. Geri was the other pillar of this project.</p><p>- <strong>Dezső Herter</strong>: graphic designer (BA, Metropolitan University, Budapest). Dezső was responsible for the visual design of the application’s pages. In addition, he coded methods in Java and html, and created the Bibliography page.</p><p>- <strong>Tamás Lengvári</strong>: currently student of law at ELTE-ÁJK, Budapest. Tamás developed the structure of the database, coded methods in different classes, and created the Custom Error Page.</p><p>- <strong>Balázs Csörgő</strong>: expert in the Waldorf education method; Balázs was responsible mainly for coding user interfaces and html pages.</p><p>- <strong>Gábor Erdős</strong>: Egyptologist (MA, PhD, ELTE-BTK Budapest), Assyriologist (MA, ELTE-BTK, Budapest) and 3D graphic artist, and product owner; Gábor laid down the foundation of the database and coded methods in Java and html.</p>','about_text'), ('<p>- Grayson, A.K. Assyrian Rulers of the Early First Millennium BC (1114-859) (RIMA 2). Toronto, 1991.</p><p>- Grayson, A.K. Assyrian Rulers of the Early First Millennium BC (858-745) (RIMA 3). Toronto, 1996.</p>','bibliography_text'), ('Confirm your registration','EMAIL_SUBJECT'), ('Click on the link to confirm your registration and set a password.','EMAIL_TEXT'), ('Your username is: ','EMAIL_TEXT_START');
